</taxonomicName>
Baker.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
Leaves consistently moderately to deeply 3, 5 or 7-lobed from stem bases to apices, with irregular, pinnate secondary lobing present on central lobe at least; central lobe to 50 mm long, lanceolate to elliptic or rhomboid, lateral lobes to 33 mm long, oblong to narrowly so, central lobe largest to lobes more or less equal in length and width. Male flowers on 1.7-3.7 mm long pedicels, tepals 2.3-3.7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.0-2.2 mm, torus (1.5-)1.9-3.4 mm in diam.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Endemic to South Africa in Limpopo and KwaZulu Natal provinces. The Limpopo specimens are from localities relatively close to those of the type subspecies in Gaza province of Mozambique.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="vernacular name(s)">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Vernacular name(s).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Not known.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Ca.</emphasis>
50 to 600 m altitude in KwaZulu Natal, and 700 to 1000 m in Limpopo. Associated geology, soils and vegetation unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="conservation">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Conservation.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wilkin &amp; Muasya" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wilkin &amp; Muasya" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Liliopsida" family="Dioscoreaceae" genus="Dioscorea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dioscorea buchananii subsp. undatiloba" order="Dioscoreales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="buchananii" subSpecies="undatiloba">Dioscorea buchananii subsp. undatiloba</taxonomicName>
has not been recorded since 1921 in either Limpopo or KwaZulu Natal and is known from only six specimens. However, pending urgently needed searches to find extant populations in Limpopo, KwaZulu Natal and the intervening areas and further research on the relationships between those populations, the most appropriate provisional conservation status assessment is DD. It is conceivable that this taxon is already extinct in part or all of its range, especially extensively developed lowland KwaZulu Natal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="uses">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Uses.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">None known</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
The specimen labelled 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Junod</emphasis>
1416 at PRE [PRE0093186-0] is male flowering material of 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Dioscoreaceae" genus="Dioscorea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dioscorea sylvatica" order="Dioscoreales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sylvatica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Dioscorea sylvatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ecklon. This explains the placement of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wilkin &amp; Muasya" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wilkin &amp; Muasya" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Liliopsida" family="Dioscoreaceae" genus="Dioscorea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dioscorea junodii" order="Dioscoreales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="junodii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Dioscorea junodii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the synonymy of that species in 
<bibRefCitation author="Govaerts, R" journalOrPublisher="The Board of Trustees of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew" pageId="13" pageNumber="64" publicationUrl="http://www.kew.org/wcsp/monocots/" refId="B8" refString="Govaerts, R, Wilkin, P, 2015. World Checklist of Dioscoreaceae. The Board of Trustees of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, http://www.kew.org/wcsp/monocots/ [accessed 30 January 2015]" title="World Checklist of Dioscoreaceae" url="http://www.kew.org/wcsp/monocots/" year="2015">Govaerts and Wilkin (2015)</bibRefCitation>
. However, Burtt Davy would have examined and described the K sheet cited above, hence its holotype status and synonymy under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wilkin &amp; Muasya" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Wilkin &amp; Muasya" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Liliopsida" family="Dioscoreaceae" genus="Dioscorea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dioscorea buchananii subsp. undatiloba" order="Dioscoreales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="buchananii" subSpecies="undatiloba">Dioscorea buchananii subsp. undatiloba</taxonomicName>
. No specimen of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Junod</emphasis>
1416 appears to be preserved at G or Z based on their online databases.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
